ks a tough-on-crime, zero tolerance policy will stop bullying is misinformed about social psychology. Equal funding that is not dependent on property values would improve schools everywhere. Parents have a responsibility to seek the best available options for their kids. I don't think parent involvement improves schools, it just creates social cliques of self-righteous know-it-alls who want to control everyone else. Public schools are failing special needs students, so it makes sense for parents of kids with special needs to look elsewhere. We don't live in a country that really wants an informed population, because if that were a national value or priority, we would have it. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="992" language="en" documentId="3426" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Molly43" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:13PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="12" thumbsDown="0" origId="3426" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="992"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>